WEBVTT

00:00:00.660 --> 00:00:01.860
All right, how are you, everyone?

00:00:01.860 --> 00:00:04.100
And thank you for being here.

00:00:04.100 --> 00:00:08.540
So, let me start with this post from social media

00:00:08.540 --> 00:00:10.380
that many of you might relate with

00:00:10.380 --> 00:00:12.940
about offering to help someone with their data.

00:00:12.940 --> 00:00:15.580
And then we encounter something slightly ridiculous,

00:00:15.580 --> 00:00:17.840
in this case, bold equals negative.

00:00:18.840 --> 00:00:22.360
Literally meaning that in a data set or a table,

00:00:22.360 --> 00:00:25.340
instead of actual minus signs,

00:00:25.340 --> 00:00:28.559
the negative values were indicated with bold text.

00:00:28.559 --> 00:00:29.559
That happens.

00:00:29.600 --> 00:00:32.560
So, we start to wonder, who does that?

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:33.400
Right?

00:00:33.400 --> 00:00:34.400
Who's doing that?

00:00:34.400 --> 00:00:36.040
But before we get to that,

00:00:36.040 --> 00:00:38.740
let me define what that refers to.

00:00:39.639 --> 00:00:42.639
And that refers to encoding data as formatting,

00:00:43.680 --> 00:00:45.740
which is this very common practice

00:00:45.740 --> 00:00:48.520
of usually storing and sharing data,

00:00:48.520 --> 00:00:50.040
often in spreadsheets,

00:00:50.040 --> 00:00:55.040
and then using formatting to intersperse and layer data

00:00:55.320 --> 00:00:57.480
where it probably shouldn't be.

00:00:57.480 --> 00:00:59.000
So, let's look at one example.

00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:01.880
This is from the real world, just a little simplified,

00:01:01.880 --> 00:01:06.459
where we get the classic bold indicates negative values

00:01:06.459 --> 00:01:08.760
for this permeability variable,

00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:12.339
and also some cell colors, because why not?

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:15.639
Let's look at another example

00:01:16.839 --> 00:01:19.980
where we have different colors for the text

00:01:19.980 --> 00:01:23.120
being used to indicate the units for the variables.

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:26.639
So, you have black for pounds, blue for kilograms,

00:01:26.639 --> 00:01:28.599
and then we have further information

00:01:29.160 --> 00:01:30.000
about one of these variables,

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:31.559
the one that says microchipped,

00:01:31.559 --> 00:01:35.480
encoded as the cell color or cell highlight color

00:01:35.480 --> 00:01:37.519
or background color, whatever we call it.

00:01:38.419 --> 00:01:42.760
So, now we can start to wonder, who does that?

00:01:42.760 --> 00:01:44.879
And the answer is, a lot of people,

00:01:44.879 --> 00:01:49.680
because there are over a billion spreadsheet users out there

00:01:49.680 --> 00:01:53.760
in industry and research and government.

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:56.940
And anytime anyone has looked at public collections

00:01:56.940 --> 00:01:59.139
of spreadsheets, myself included,

00:01:59.139 --> 00:02:02.900
between 25 to 60% of public spreadsheets

00:02:02.900 --> 00:02:05.739
use either cell or text formatting or both,

00:02:05.739 --> 00:02:07.540
and it won't always be used

00:02:07.540 --> 00:02:09.880
just for emphasis or decoration.

00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:12.880
So, a lot of the time, with so many spreadsheets out there,

00:02:13.839 --> 00:02:15.740
data will be encoded as formatting.

00:02:15.740 --> 00:02:17.320
It's just hard to know,

00:02:17.320 --> 00:02:19.960
or it's hard to identify that programmatically,

00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:22.039
so I can't have that figure for you.

00:02:23.039 --> 00:02:27.240
And this is happening partly because

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:29.679
we go into data analysis with the tools we know

00:02:29.679 --> 00:02:31.520
or the tools we know about,

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:33.080
not necessarily the tools we need,

00:02:33.080 --> 00:02:34.279
and a lot of the time,

00:02:34.279 --> 00:02:36.699
this happens to be spreadsheet software.

00:02:38.899 --> 00:02:42.419
So, before anyone starts getting too outraged,

00:02:42.419 --> 00:02:46.539
let me revisit the data from the Tibet Clinic

00:02:46.539 --> 00:02:49.160
and show you what's actually possible

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:52.059
and something we can do right now in R.

00:02:52.059 --> 00:02:54.600
So, let's look at this table or this spreadsheet.

00:02:54.600 --> 00:02:56.520
It just looks nice here.

00:02:56.520 --> 00:02:59.759
And specifically, the two problematic columns

00:02:59.759 --> 00:03:01.660
with the formatting that we see there.

00:03:03.279 --> 00:03:04.440
I'll show the code later on,

00:03:04.440 --> 00:03:06.320
but we can actually do this now.

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:09.240
So, import the cell values,

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:11.759
import the formatting, and it gets,

00:03:11.759 --> 00:03:14.600
we convert it into these notations inside parentheses,

00:03:14.600 --> 00:03:18.679
telling us which of the values are the text is bold

00:03:18.679 --> 00:03:20.639
and colorful.

00:03:20.639 --> 00:03:23.740
This is ARGB color code.

00:03:23.740 --> 00:03:25.080
And for the other variable,

00:03:25.080 --> 00:03:26.839
we know now which of these rows

00:03:26.839 --> 00:03:30.720
or which of these values has the background highlight color.

00:03:32.919 --> 00:03:35.660
And with a little bit of data wrangling,

00:03:35.660 --> 00:03:39.639
we can actually arrive at a more analysis-ready,

00:03:39.639 --> 00:03:42.100
machine-readable version of the data.

00:03:42.100 --> 00:03:44.880
The information that was encoded only in the formatting,

00:03:44.880 --> 00:03:49.320
it's now made explicit in its own variable, like units.

00:03:49.320 --> 00:03:51.240
And the other piece of information

00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:53.759
that was encoded through highlight color

00:03:53.759 --> 00:03:57.880
or cell background fill is now also made explicit

00:03:57.880 --> 00:04:01.759
in its own column, chip status here.

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:06.520
So, by now, I hope we all agree

00:04:06.520 --> 00:04:08.220
that using data as formatting

00:04:08.220 --> 00:04:10.259
is not necessarily the best idea.

00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:14.300
First of all, because it doesn't play very well

00:04:14.660 --> 00:04:17.899
with the modern or the current data science stack,

00:04:17.899 --> 00:04:21.940
regardless of programming languages or tools or whatever.

00:04:22.980 --> 00:04:25.940
And also problematic is that

00:04:25.940 --> 00:04:28.940
this introduces accessibility issues.

00:04:28.940 --> 00:04:31.700
Formatting like that is not good for screen readers.

00:04:31.700 --> 00:04:34.660
It's also not good for colorblind people.

00:04:34.660 --> 00:04:35.739
So that's an issue.

00:04:36.940 --> 00:04:38.899
And again, these kinds of things happen

00:04:38.899 --> 00:04:40.420
because spreadsheets,

00:04:40.420 --> 00:04:43.260
they relax the rules of data organization.

00:04:43.260 --> 00:04:46.779
As humans, we can typically look at ambiguities

00:04:46.779 --> 00:04:49.299
and resolve them either through context

00:04:49.299 --> 00:04:51.100
or just from our prior knowledge.

00:04:51.100 --> 00:04:53.059
And machines, not so much.

00:04:56.980 --> 00:04:59.380
But now let me tell you what we can do,

00:04:59.380 --> 00:05:00.859
what we are doing already,

00:05:00.859 --> 00:05:02.700
what we can do moving forward.

00:05:02.700 --> 00:05:06.399
And I feel like what we do and what we can do

00:05:06.399 --> 00:05:08.140
tend to fall into one of the following

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:11.859
three categories or approaches.

00:05:11.859 --> 00:05:15.660
So the first and the more ideal one

00:05:15.660 --> 00:05:18.140
would be to prevent this thing from happening

00:05:18.140 --> 00:05:19.660
in the first place.

00:05:19.660 --> 00:05:22.019
To me, it'd be great if school children

00:05:22.019 --> 00:05:24.700
and college students and our own colleagues

00:05:24.700 --> 00:05:26.779
would read these kinds of resources.

00:05:26.779 --> 00:05:29.260
And in particular, this guide here

00:05:29.260 --> 00:05:31.220
about data organization in spreadsheets,

00:05:31.220 --> 00:05:34.380
which I consider to me the ultimate reading material

00:05:34.380 --> 00:05:37.239
for organizing data in spreadsheets.

00:05:37.239 --> 00:05:39.940
And this particular resource includes

00:05:39.940 --> 00:05:42.859
good advice of not using data in formatting.

00:05:44.140 --> 00:05:46.579
But that's not always the case.

00:05:46.579 --> 00:05:48.179
Another example or another approach

00:05:48.179 --> 00:05:49.980
would be to just ignore the problem.

00:05:51.179 --> 00:05:53.459
And we can maybe in a particular project,

00:05:53.459 --> 00:05:56.540
in a particular field, in a particular job,

00:05:56.540 --> 00:05:59.019
we might not even encounter spreadsheets,

00:05:59.019 --> 00:06:02.100
let alone colorful formatted spreadsheets.

00:06:02.100 --> 00:06:05.040
So in that case, we could be like the guilty dog there.

00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:07.000
If we don't look at it, it's not there.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:08.420
So it's not really our problem

00:06:08.420 --> 00:06:11.160
and we can just move on with whatever we need to do.

00:06:12.500 --> 00:06:14.420
But that's also not always the case.

00:06:14.420 --> 00:06:18.100
And then we arrive at the third sort of broad category

00:06:18.100 --> 00:06:21.140
of either having to go and fix things manually,

00:06:21.140 --> 00:06:25.600
edit the files ourselves, ask for them to be reworked

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:27.380
and then sent back to us.

00:06:27.380 --> 00:06:31.739
Or if we really want to do it programmatically

00:06:31.739 --> 00:06:33.459
in R or Python or whatever,

00:06:33.459 --> 00:06:37.100
then we get these numerous case-by-case approaches

00:06:37.100 --> 00:06:37.920
like this one here.

00:06:38.420 --> 00:06:41.600
This is part of a two-part blog series,

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:43.839
quite recent actually, and I liked it,

00:06:43.839 --> 00:06:48.160
where this involved edits to the underlying C code

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:50.339
to read Excel to be able to pull in

00:06:50.339 --> 00:06:52.040
and deal with conditional formatting.

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:55.839
So not something a lot of us can do.

00:06:55.839 --> 00:06:58.720
Maybe here, yes, but not me personally.

00:06:58.720 --> 00:07:01.959
Or this other example I have here from last year

00:07:01.959 --> 00:07:05.399
where poor Jeremy was loading in like 15 different packages

00:07:05.399 --> 00:07:07.559
and having to write a ton of code

00:07:07.559 --> 00:07:11.399
to deal with what was a fairly simple table

00:07:11.399 --> 00:07:13.339
except it was made problematic

00:07:13.339 --> 00:07:16.019
because of data encoded as formatting.

00:07:17.320 --> 00:07:18.519
And these are just a few examples,

00:07:18.519 --> 00:07:21.480
but there's tons of these kinds of things,

00:07:21.480 --> 00:07:24.760
of people working through formatted spreadsheets

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:28.440
with whatever tooling they can get their hands on in R.

00:07:29.920 --> 00:07:33.200
But I'm not here to make fun or take cheap shots

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:35.079
at spreadsheets and their users.

00:07:35.760 --> 00:07:37.320
Rather, I want to mention now

00:07:37.320 --> 00:07:40.399
what the community has been doing to move forward

00:07:40.399 --> 00:07:43.040
and to actually enable us to work with this,

00:07:43.040 --> 00:07:45.119
including some of my own contributions.

00:07:46.279 --> 00:07:49.959
And I'll start with this one from myself.

00:07:49.959 --> 00:07:53.519
So this is a blog post from 2016,

00:07:53.519 --> 00:07:54.920
so about nine years ago,

00:07:54.920 --> 00:07:58.320
the first of many blog posts of mine that used,

00:07:58.320 --> 00:08:02.200
well, the first of many blog posts of mine on the topic.

00:08:02.200 --> 00:08:05.720
And at the time, this was a bit created out of frustration,

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:07.799
but I tried to be nice when I wrote it.

00:08:07.799 --> 00:08:09.480
So I just mentioned three bad things,

00:08:09.480 --> 00:08:11.440
three things, bad practices,

00:08:11.440 --> 00:08:14.200
or three things to avoid altogether,

00:08:14.200 --> 00:08:19.200
including not using the whole formatting as data.

00:08:20.440 --> 00:08:22.959
And at the time, I didn't think much of it,

00:08:22.959 --> 00:08:26.160
but this post itself was quite well-received,

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:28.279
and I realized that it was the content

00:08:28.279 --> 00:08:30.559
and the principles were starting to be incorporated

00:08:30.559 --> 00:08:35.000
directly into proper data science teaching materials,

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:36.799
which was quite motivating for me.

00:08:37.799 --> 00:08:40.640
And later on, we formalized that

00:08:40.640 --> 00:08:42.719
into the scientific publication.

00:08:42.719 --> 00:08:45.919
A bit niche and aimed at not just biologists,

00:08:45.919 --> 00:08:47.919
but mammal biologists,

00:08:47.919 --> 00:08:50.119
but still, I'm pretty proud of this work.

00:08:51.880 --> 00:08:54.000
And in parallel during this time,

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.640
I also tried to come up with some tools of my own

00:08:56.640 --> 00:08:58.520
to deal with messy data.

00:08:58.520 --> 00:09:01.400
So this is my unhead.r package,

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:03.039
the first package I developed.

00:09:03.039 --> 00:09:06.119
It was, I think, released initially in 2018.

00:09:07.239 --> 00:09:10.239
It started as a package for cleaning messy datasets,

00:09:10.239 --> 00:09:12.039
and later on, I added some functions

00:09:12.039 --> 00:09:14.400
to expose the formatting in spreadsheets

00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:17.320
and just glue it to the cell values like we saw earlier.

00:09:19.159 --> 00:09:22.359
And this is possible because I leveraged existing tools

00:09:22.359 --> 00:09:25.239
built by other very clever people,

00:09:25.280 --> 00:09:28.119
and because the formatting is there

00:09:28.119 --> 00:09:29.320
in the spreadsheet files.

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:32.200
It's just hidden in underlying XML

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:35.119
that we can parse and fiddle with,

00:09:35.119 --> 00:09:37.320
and then we can just expose that formatting

00:09:37.320 --> 00:09:39.080
and have it at our disposal.

00:09:40.960 --> 00:09:45.599
And I guess through my work with the package

00:09:45.599 --> 00:09:50.239
and with me ranting or blogging about spreadsheets

00:09:50.239 --> 00:09:51.960
in my blog and social media,

00:09:51.960 --> 00:09:54.119
I was invited to contribute to this piece.

00:09:54.119 --> 00:09:58.799
It was a nice little article about coming up with tips

00:09:58.799 --> 00:10:01.599
for better spreadsheets from a data science perspective.

00:10:02.479 --> 00:10:05.799
And well, of course, when I'm quoted in this text,

00:10:05.799 --> 00:10:09.559
I made a clown out of myself about using color coding

00:10:09.559 --> 00:10:11.599
and then forgetting my color codes.

00:10:11.599 --> 00:10:13.640
But anyway, I just want to mention this

00:10:13.640 --> 00:10:18.640
because promoting and coming up and using good practices,

00:10:19.559 --> 00:10:20.719
it's still an ongoing topic.

00:10:20.719 --> 00:10:23.000
This is a follow-up piece from last month.

00:10:23.039 --> 00:10:24.960
So again, more things to consider

00:10:24.960 --> 00:10:27.479
before we get into spreadsheets.

00:10:29.919 --> 00:10:34.239
And also in parallel, beyond just good practices

00:10:34.239 --> 00:10:37.640
and promoting things and trying to educate people,

00:10:37.640 --> 00:10:39.679
for the past 10 or 12 years,

00:10:39.679 --> 00:10:41.719
a lot of people in this community

00:10:41.719 --> 00:10:44.919
and in R and data science and programming in general

00:10:44.919 --> 00:10:47.320
have been developing and improving

00:10:47.320 --> 00:10:49.960
and maintaining some really nice tools

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:51.799
that we can use for that.

00:10:51.799 --> 00:10:55.679
So now we can read spreadsheets, write spreadsheets.

00:10:55.679 --> 00:10:58.119
We can work with files that are in the cloud.

00:10:58.119 --> 00:10:59.559
And for the most part,

00:10:59.559 --> 00:11:01.440
there's a lot of very good documentation

00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:02.599
that we can learn from.

00:11:07.320 --> 00:11:09.520
And now let me bring together,

00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:12.760
or at least show you how this all came together for me

00:11:12.760 --> 00:11:16.119
with a very recent example in which using all this work,

00:11:16.119 --> 00:11:19.239
I was able to actually help others

00:11:19.239 --> 00:11:21.599
in a really satisfying way for me.

00:11:22.400 --> 00:11:24.520
So earlier this year,

00:11:24.520 --> 00:11:26.440
a team of famous scientists

00:11:26.440 --> 00:11:29.159
that do some very cool research in Antarctica,

00:11:29.159 --> 00:11:30.000
they came to me,

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:31.880
they have spreadsheets that look like this,

00:11:31.880 --> 00:11:35.719
except way wider, but just as colorful.

00:11:35.719 --> 00:11:37.719
And they had this nice little challenge.

00:11:38.799 --> 00:11:40.799
It said that on the days marked in yellow,

00:11:40.799 --> 00:11:43.679
we sampled two individuals from each aquarium.

00:11:43.679 --> 00:11:46.679
So they needed to know the sampling dates

00:11:46.679 --> 00:11:50.239
to account for the survival of the different individuals

00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:52.880
in a really high stakes experiment.

00:11:52.880 --> 00:11:54.119
And the information's there.

00:11:54.119 --> 00:11:57.520
So they recorded the sampling dates,

00:11:57.520 --> 00:12:00.020
except they recorded it through formatting.

00:12:01.119 --> 00:12:04.679
And we could actually just go through the files manually.

00:12:04.679 --> 00:12:08.359
And okay, so that date has yellow, that's a sampling date.

00:12:08.359 --> 00:12:10.960
And we repeat that for all the experimental conditions

00:12:10.960 --> 00:12:11.960
and for all the days.

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:14.640
And this experiment was many months long.

00:12:14.640 --> 00:12:18.159
So it's still doable, but not reproducible

00:12:18.159 --> 00:12:21.479
and prone to human error if we do it like that.

00:12:21.479 --> 00:12:24.840
And for once, I was able to tell this team,

00:12:24.840 --> 00:12:26.640
I actually know how to do it.

00:12:26.640 --> 00:12:29.000
I can start working straight away.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:31.460
And I'll email you the answer in 20 minutes.

00:12:32.359 --> 00:12:33.679
So I'll show you what I,

00:12:33.679 --> 00:12:36.099
with a simplified example, how this works.

00:12:37.520 --> 00:12:41.239
So if we have the spreadsheet that looks like that,

00:12:41.239 --> 00:12:43.479
we can just read it with Read Excel.

00:12:44.520 --> 00:12:47.200
And we get the cell contents.

00:12:47.200 --> 00:12:48.039
That's fine.

00:12:48.859 --> 00:12:51.119
The dates are mangled because, you know, spreadsheets.

00:12:51.119 --> 00:12:52.760
But we can fix that.

00:12:54.760 --> 00:12:56.520
So if we use the unheader package

00:12:56.520 --> 00:12:58.840
I was talking about earlier,

00:12:58.840 --> 00:13:02.200
we can use this function called annotate mf,

00:13:02.200 --> 00:13:05.320
in this case, all, to work across all columns.

00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:07.919
And mf stands for meaningful formatting,

00:13:07.919 --> 00:13:11.119
which is another way to call this practice.

00:13:12.239 --> 00:13:15.099
And we get something like I was showing you earlier.

00:13:15.099 --> 00:13:19.219
So we get the contents for the cells.

00:13:19.219 --> 00:13:22.320
And also, this little annotation in parentheses

00:13:22.320 --> 00:13:27.020
of which of these values had a highlight color.

00:13:27.020 --> 00:13:29.500
And that's the color code for yellow.

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:32.919
So we have a table that looks like this,

00:13:32.919 --> 00:13:33.859
except way longer.

00:13:33.859 --> 00:13:37.119
We've identified which are the sampling dates,

00:13:37.119 --> 00:13:40.460
or at least which columns have the yellow in them.

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:43.919
Can do a bit of data transformation.

00:13:43.919 --> 00:13:46.799
So we reshape the data into a long format.

00:13:48.200 --> 00:13:50.940
Fix the dates, because we can fix the dates.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:55.640
And now we have a long format version of the data

00:13:55.640 --> 00:13:58.500
where we can actually now filter for the tags

00:13:58.500 --> 00:13:59.840
that indicate the formatting.

00:13:59.840 --> 00:14:00.979
If we have different colors,

00:14:00.979 --> 00:14:03.159
we could just filter through color codes

00:14:03.159 --> 00:14:07.159
and just arrive at what I was being asked,

00:14:07.159 --> 00:14:09.320
which is tell me the sampling dates

00:14:09.320 --> 00:14:12.460
for each experimental condition and each file.

00:14:12.460 --> 00:14:16.340
So that was actually a proud moment of mine.

00:14:16.340 --> 00:14:19.179
And it seemed impressive to the team,

00:14:19.179 --> 00:14:21.419
but it was something I've been doing for years now,

00:14:21.419 --> 00:14:25.099
except for the most part, it was my own personal work.

00:14:25.099 --> 00:14:28.219
But I was happy to show this to other people,

00:14:28.219 --> 00:14:30.099
and then they incorporated that

00:14:30.099 --> 00:14:32.059
into their own analysis workflow,

00:14:32.059 --> 00:14:34.640
because they were doing survival analysis in R anyway.

00:14:34.640 --> 00:14:35.900
So that was pretty cool.

00:14:37.380 --> 00:14:40.179
And it was all based on this simple principle

00:14:40.179 --> 00:14:42.659
of we import cell values, we import formatting,

00:14:42.659 --> 00:14:44.659
and we translate the formatting to strings

00:14:44.659 --> 00:14:47.659
and just glue it to the cell values.

00:14:47.659 --> 00:14:50.020
That gave me an idea last year,

00:14:50.020 --> 00:14:53.119
translate that instead to GT specifications,

00:14:54.400 --> 00:14:57.619
which led to the 4GTS package.

00:14:57.619 --> 00:14:59.799
All it does is converts a formatted spreadsheet

00:14:59.799 --> 00:15:02.219
to a gray table, or a GT object.

00:15:04.780 --> 00:15:06.219
And that would look like this.

00:15:06.219 --> 00:15:07.419
The spreadsheet looks like this.

00:15:07.419 --> 00:15:10.039
I added some format, I added some color,

00:15:10.880 --> 00:15:12.760
I added underline, italic, bold.

00:15:14.599 --> 00:15:17.000
Read that file, and that there is an actual

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.520
HTML GT object in my slide.

00:15:22.280 --> 00:15:24.799
This is one piece of feedback I know of

00:15:24.799 --> 00:15:26.820
about the package from Kelly.

00:15:28.559 --> 00:15:30.119
It does work halfway.

00:15:30.119 --> 00:15:32.799
I've been using that for, I think,

00:15:32.799 --> 00:15:35.159
well, for almost a year I've been using it

00:15:35.159 --> 00:15:39.719
to create tables in reports and slides,

00:15:40.400 --> 00:15:41.679
and for teaching, so it works quite well.

00:15:41.679 --> 00:15:43.960
And a nice surprise, or update for everyone,

00:15:43.960 --> 00:15:47.359
is that thanks to the work of Fernanda Aguirre-Ruiz,

00:15:47.359 --> 00:15:50.640
4GTS now also exists in Python.

00:15:51.520 --> 00:15:53.840
The logo is cooler, I think.

00:15:53.840 --> 00:15:55.559
We both work on it together.

00:15:55.559 --> 00:15:57.960
And it works as well, so this is code

00:15:57.960 --> 00:16:00.919
that actually was evaluated when rendering my slides.

00:16:00.919 --> 00:16:04.140
We get the same GT object.

00:16:04.140 --> 00:16:06.340
That's an HTML table, it looks pretty good.

00:16:07.340 --> 00:16:10.820
So I'll wrap up saying that if we keep using

00:16:10.820 --> 00:16:13.460
and following and promoting good practices,

00:16:13.460 --> 00:16:16.979
and use existing tools, and share awareness

00:16:16.979 --> 00:16:19.940
of the existing tools, we can coexist

00:16:19.940 --> 00:16:23.260
with formatted spreadsheets, which are kind of

00:16:23.260 --> 00:16:25.619
like the fossil fuels of data,

00:16:25.619 --> 00:16:27.940
that they'll still be around for a while.

00:16:27.940 --> 00:16:31.619
And then I'll just leave you with the title

00:16:31.619 --> 00:16:34.299
and tagline for one of my other blog posts.

00:16:34.299 --> 00:16:36.739
Formatted spreadsheets can still work in R,

00:16:36.739 --> 00:16:37.700
it's not too late.

00:16:38.799 --> 00:16:40.260
Thank you.

